hrough defense challenges to what prosecutors claimed to be an infallible technology. Although this process was fraught with controversy, inefficiency, and personal antagonism, the quality of DNA evidence improved dramatically as a result. Aronson argues, however, that the dream of a perfect identification technology remains unrealized.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aDNA fingerprintingxHistoryxGreat Britain. 0aDNA fingerprintingxHistoryxUnited States. 0aDNA fingerprintingzGreat BritainxHistory. 0aDNA fingerprintingzUnited StatesxHistory. 0aForensic geneticsxHistoryxGreat Britain. 0aForensic geneticsxHistoryxUnited States. 0aForensic geneticszGreat BritainxHistory. 0aForensic geneticszUnited StatesxHistory. 7aSCIENCE / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertRutgers University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311068861040uhttps://doi.org/10.36019/978081354383340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780813543833423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780813543833.jpg  a978-3-11-068861-0  Rutgers University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_ESTMALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA18STMEE  aPDA5EBK